<!---->  </span><span class=""> has added a feature to its job listings that lets candidates write a quick comment to the hiring manager about why they are a good fit for the role. In theory, that comment (and the different coloring) will catch the hiring manager's eye and help you stand out against other candidates. However, is it possible to stand out when everyone uses the feature?  I feel like this is like what happened with news and Twitter. One outlet started putting BREAKING in all caps at the front of their news tweets years ago, everyone copied them and now "BREAKING" carries no weight. Also, if I were a job seeker, this would tell me that this was created because candidates don't get noticed on ZipRecruiter. I'm honestly confused, but hopefully, it's free. </span><span class="font-[700]"><a href="https://www.businesswire.com/news/home/20260122811841/en/ZipRecruiter-Now-Lets-Job-Seekers-Jump-to-the-Top-of-the-Resume-Pile" target="_blank" data-tracking-control-name="article-ssr-frontend-pulse_little-text-block" data-tracking-will-navigate="" data-test-link="">Read the full release<!----></a></span><span class="">.</span><!---->
